[
    {
        "content": "<p>We don't have this, right? Given <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> two <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>-algebras, I want the compositum <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">LM</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>, some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span>-algebra containing <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> and generated by them. Do we want an <code>IsCompositum</code> predicate and if so, what should it eat? In my application (class field theory) I need an explicit construction (and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span>,<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> are unrelated extensions of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>K</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span> and both types). Any thoughts on the best way to formalize this if we don't have it already?</p>",
        "id": 555112513,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1762952450
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do the conditions that you specify determine LM uniquely?</p>",
        "id": 555112974,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1762952603
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think that I've seen this mostly in the context of subfields of a given field.  Where the important part is that there is a common ambient for both.</p>",
        "id": 555113099,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1762952648
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm thinking of adding a cube root of 2 to Q and then the compositum of this field with itself could be either just itself or the splitting field of <code>x ^ 3 - 2</code>.</p>",
        "id": 555113553,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1762952771
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe you could use any subalgebra of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>K</mi></msub><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\otimes_K M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> with the conditions that you mention?</p>",
        "id": 555114281,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1762952951
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No they don't, but if one of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> are Galois then they do.</p>",
        "id": 555130620,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1762957186
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, I think that the tensor product should contain all possibilities.</p>",
        "id": 555131399,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1762957317
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Up to isomorphism, of course.)</p>",
        "id": 555131459,
        "sender_full_name": "Damiano Testa",
        "timestamp": 1762957333
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am almost sure everything we have in mathlib is about subobjects of an ambient space.</p>",
        "id": 555143945,
        "sender_full_name": "Riccardo Brasca",
        "timestamp": 1762960021
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>IsCompositum</code> probably takes <code>[Algebra L E] [Algebra M E]</code> and says that <code>(algebraMap L E).fieldRange \\sup (algebraMap M E).fieldRange = \\top</code></p>",
        "id": 555147869,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1762960916
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah that's basically what we did.</p>",
        "id": 555149475,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1762961278
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Don’t you want to take the quotient of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><msub><mo>⊗</mo><mi>K</mi></msub><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L\\otimes_K M</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\"><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3283em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> by a maximal ideal?</p>",
        "id": 556614215,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1763221233
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that is also what we did. we made both Compositum and IsCompositum.</p>",
        "id": 556614261,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1763221271
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ok cool</p>",
        "id": 556614298,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1763221303
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would say that you don't want a construction because it depends on choices in general, but <code>IsCompositum E K L M</code> would say that the E-algebra <code>M</code> is generated by its subalgebras <code>K</code> and <code>L</code> makes sense. Then, you'd need the existence of compositum and their uniqueness (up to isomorphism) if as you say <code>K</code> or <code>L</code>is Galois over <code>E</code>, or if one of them is <code>K</code> is “regular”  (which is more or less the definition of regular, with possible characterizations in terms of tensor product with alg. closure of <code>K</code>)</p>",
        "id": 556619848,
        "sender_full_name": "Antoine Chambert-Loir",
        "timestamp": 1763226661
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>we can still make an arbitrary one, it's the philosophy of junk value</p>",
        "id": 556619882,
        "sender_full_name": "Kenny Lau",
        "timestamp": 1763226706
    }
]